"Schtickzelle N., WallisDeVries M.F., Baguette M.","Using surrogate data in population viability analysis: The case of the critically endangered cranberry fritillary butterfly",2005,"Oikos","109","1",,"89","100",,,10.1111/j.0030-1299.2005.13745.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-17144400417&partnerID=40&md5=97460e48802d529e6a98fbe5da5db4ec","Biodiversity Research Centre, Catholic Univ. Louvain, Croix du Sud 4-5, BE-1348 Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium; Vlinderstichting/Dutch Butterfly C., P.O. Box 506, NL-6700 AM Wageningen, Netherlands","Schtickzelle, N., Biodiversity Research Centre, Catholic Univ. Louvain, Croix du Sud 4-5, BE-1348 Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium; WallisDeVries, M.F., Vlinderstichting/Dutch Butterfly C., P.O. Box 506, NL-6700 AM Wageningen, Netherlands; Baguette, M., Biodiversity Research Centre, Catholic Univ. Louvain, Croix du Sud 4-5, BE-1348 Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium","Population viability analyses (PVA) are central tools for the management of threatened populations. However, the parameterisation of effective PVA models is very demanding in high quality data, which are often impossible to collect on endangered populations. Here we propose the use of a generalisation strategy to bypass this limitation: management measures for an endangered metapopulation of the cranberry fritillary butterfly in the Netherlands are evaluated with RAMAS/GIS by using parameters estimated from a healthier metapopulation in Belgium. The Belgian metapopulation seems viable, with stable abundance and number of local populations, despite their erratic dynamics, whereas the Dutch metapopulation shows a continuous decline in the course of time, with many vacant habitat patches. Simulations of various scenarios indicated that (1) large scale restoration of habitat patches would be necessary to ensure long-term survival of the species in the Netherlands as not enough suitable habitats are currently remaining; and that (2) global warming is expected to put a major threat on both metapopulations by reducing the growth rate of this glacial relict species, and/or increasing environmental stochasticity (amplified climatic variations). Copyright © OIKOS 2005.",,"butterfly; conservation management; endangered species; population viability analysis; wildlife management; Belgium; Benelux; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Europe; Netherlands; Western Europe; World; Fritillaria (angiosperm); Potato virus A; Vaccinium macrocarpon",,,,,,"Akçakaya, H.R., RAMAS/GIS: Linking spatial data with population viability analysis (version 4.0) (2002) Applied Biomathematics; Akçakaya, H.R., Sjögren-Gulve, P., Population viability analyses in conservation planning: An overview (2000) Ecol. Bull., 48, pp. 9-21; Baguette, M., Long distance dispersal and landscape occupancy in a metapopulation of the cranberry fritillary butterfly (2003) Ecography, 26, pp. 153-160; Baguette, M., Goffart, P., De Bast, B., Modification de la distribution et du statut des Lépidoptè res Rhopalocères en Belgique depuis 1900 (1992) Mém. Soc. R. Belge d'Entomol., 35, pp. 591-596; Baguette, M., Schtickzelle, N., Local population dynamics are important to the conservation of metapopulations in highly fragmented landscapes (2003) J. Appl. Ecol., 40, pp. 404-412; Barascud, B., Martin, J.F., Baguette, M., Genetic consequences of an introduction-colonization process in an endangered butterfly species (1999) J. Evol. Biol., 12, pp. 697-709; Bart, J., Acceptance criteria for using individual-based models to make management decisions (1995) Ecol. Appl., 5, pp. 411-420; Beissinger, S.R., McCullough, D.R., (2002) Population Viability Analysis, , The Univ. of Chicago Press; Beissinger, S.R., Westphal, M.I., On the use of demographic models of population viability in endangered species management (1998) J. Wildlife Manage., 62, pp. 821-841; Brook, B.W., O'Grady, J.J., Chapman, A.P., Predictive accuracy of population viability analysis in conservation biology (2000) Nature, 404, pp. 385-387; Bur